---
/**
 * DoorDash hub. The deduction methodology lives here because it is identical in
 * all 51 states — leaving it on every state page made them 83% alike and put
 * three of them under the substance line. The state pages keep what actually
 * varies: the state's own tax on the resulting profit, its rules, and its
 * borders.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import QuickEstimator from '../../components/calculators/QuickEstimator.tsx';
import { stateList } from '../../data/states';
import { stateSlug } from '../../lib/slug';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';
import { findPlatform, platformExample, deductionLabel, MILE_RATE, MILE_SOURCE } from '../../lib/platform-copy';

const platform = findPlatform('doordash')!;
const ex = platformExample(platform)!;
---

<Base
  title="DoorDash tax calculator (2026) — mileage, deductions and what you owe"
  description="What DoorDash drivers owe for 2026. The gross on your 1099-NEC is not what you are taxed on — work through mileage at 72.5c and the rest, then pick your state."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>DoorDash tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Nothing is withheld, and the number on your {platform.incomeType} is not the number you are taxed on.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    DoorDash reports what it paid you and stops there. Self-employment tax, federal income tax and your
    state's income tax all come out of what is left after expenses — and for delivery work the largest
    expense by a distance is the car.
  </p>

  <QuickEstimator client:load defaultSeIncome={ex.gross} stateHrefBase="/doordash-tax-calculator/" />

  <h2>Mileage is the deduction that matters</h2>
  <p data-source="data/federal.ts → selfEmploymentDeductions.mileage">
    The 2026 standard business mileage rate is <strong>{(MILE_RATE * 100).toFixed(1)} cents a mile</strong>
    {' '}({MILE_SOURCE}). Every mile driven for deliveries counts — including between orders and back to
    your zone, not just the miles a customer is waiting on.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two rules worth knowing before you rely on it: you cannot claim standard mileage and actual vehicle
    costs for the same car in the same year, and standard mileage is unavailable if you have previously
    claimed MACRS depreciation on that vehicle.
  </p>

  <h2>A worked deduction stack</h2>
  <p data-source="overrides/platform-scenarios.json (illustrative scenario)">
    A driver who grossed {formatMoney(ex.gross)} across {(18000).toLocaleString()} business miles. The
    gross and the mileage are an illustration, not a claim about what drivers earn; every rate applied to
    them is from the verified 2026 dataset.
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Deduction</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {ex.lines.map((l) => (
        <tr><td data-source={l.source}>{l.label}</td><td>{formatMoney(l.amount)}</td></tr>
      ))}
      <tr class="total"><td>Total deductions</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalDeductions)}</td></tr>
      <tr class="total"><td>Net profit — the taxable figure</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netProfit)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    {Math.round(ex.deductionShare * 100)}% of the gross never reaches taxable profit. A driver who does
    not log miles is handing over the largest deduction available to them.
  </p>

  <h2>Everything DoorDash drivers can deduct</h2>
  <p data-source="data/platforms.ts → doordash.keyDeductions">
    The dataset lists {platform.keyDeductions.length} categories:
    {' '}{platform.keyDeductions.map(deductionLabel).join(', ')}. Mileage and the business share of your
    phone are the two that move the number; the rest are small but real, and they are only deductible if
    you kept the receipt.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Nothing is withheld</strong>
    DoorDash is not an employer and takes nothing out. What you owe is paid in four instalments across the
    year — see <a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">quarterly estimated payments</a>.
  </div>

  <h2>What these figures assume</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Single filer taking the standard deduction, with DoorDash as the only income.</li>
    <li>Standard mileage method rather than actual vehicle costs — you cannot use both for one car in one year.</li>
    <li>Nothing withheld, so the tax is owed in four instalments across the year.</li>
    <li>The gross and mileage in the example are an illustrative scenario. Every rate applied to them is from the verified 2026 dataset.</li>
    <li>No credits beyond those in the engine, and no state-specific credits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>DoorDash taxes by state</h2>
  <p>Your state's rate applies to that net profit. Each page works it through with that state's 2026 rules:</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {stateList.map(([, s]) => (
      <li><a href={`/doordash-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(s.name)}/`}>{s.name}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>
</Base>
